WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.000
Welcome everyone. This past September, September 2023, I had the great pleasure of sitting down in Oxford with Ian McGilchrist and Daniel Schmacktenberger, and we recorded this video.

00:12.000 --> 00:35.000
It's an intense and deep and exciting discussion in which we use our collective attention and whatever collective wisdom we were able to muster to try and address the question of the metacrisis that's facing us.

00:35.000 --> 00:48.000
This video has shown up on Daniel's channel and on Ian's channel, but I thought my audience should also have direct and specific access to it.

00:48.000 --> 01:02.000
It's a long video, but we're getting tremendous amount of positive feedback on how it's worth the time put into it. So I'm going to thank you ahead of time for your time and attention.

01:02.000 --> 01:15.000
So we are here today to discuss, I believe the title of this will be called something like the Psychological Drivers of the Metacrisis and what possible responses might look like.

01:15.000 --> 01:34.000
And so I'll start briefly with what do we mean by metacrisis and then ask you to share some of the short version of the models that you have shared at great depth in your writing and your work, and ask you to also share

01:34.000 --> 01:45.000
your opening frame so that people who aren't already familiar with your work can come along, though everybody should, if they're interested in this, go deeper. There's a lot of resources to go deeper.

01:45.000 --> 02:00.000
I'm also not assuming, since we all just know each other a tiny bit, enough to have a sense of shared interest, but not enough that we've already done this. This is extemporaneous, which is part of what makes it very interesting to me.

02:00.000 --> 02:20.000
So I'm not assuming that either of you share the exact same assessment of the metacrisis. That's not implicit in you being here, but I know from our conversations you both share a sense that the state of the world has problems and impending risks that are serious,

02:20.000 --> 02:35.000
that are not automatically resolving themselves, that are novel in history. So we can just say the challenging state of the world, what in the nature of human mind, the nature of human conditioning experience,

02:35.000 --> 02:56.000
we might even find that the term psychology or cognitive drivers are insufficient, which is fine, has brought us here, and what might a different relationship to human mind, psychology, cognition look like that might allow a more viable, better future.

02:56.000 --> 03:10.000
So just briefly on the metacrisis frame, before World War Two there was no risk that we could very quickly destroy the entire habitability of human civilization.

03:10.000 --> 03:26.000
That was brought into being with very powerful technology, nuclear weapons, and for the first time ever we had the ability to make a series of bad decisions and radically change the possibility space of the world.

03:27.000 --> 03:45.000
Before the Industrial Revolution we didn't really have the capability of destroying the biosphere at scale, that's not as fast, that takes a few hundred years, but we're at the place where the planetary boundaries in terms of species extinction, in terms of chemical pollution, in terms of many planetary boundaries are being crossed.

03:45.000 --> 04:03.000
The Stockholm Resilience Center published its update to the planetary boundaries framework just a few days ago that showed of the nine major boundaries they've identified we've radically crossed six already, which means who knows if we were to change the direction already what would happen.

04:03.000 --> 04:20.000
And that was the result of the Industrial Revolution and the technology that it made possible, moving us from half a billion people before the Industrial Revolution to eight billion people, and increasing the resource consumption per capita by about a hundred X in the industrialized world.

04:20.000 --> 04:28.000
So sixteen times the population, a hundred times the resource consumption per population, obviously without advanced tech we couldn't do that.

04:28.000 --> 04:52.000
So there's something about the crises that we're facing and then obviously AI and synthetic biology and drones and cyber weapons and the radically complicated six continent supply chain that is all very novel human technological development that wasn't true in any previous age.

04:53.000 --> 05:05.000
Without human technology there is no global existential risk that is human induced. There might be a meteor or something, but not anthropogenic catastrophic risk. So we're in a unique position in time.

05:05.000 --> 05:17.000
The poly crisis is a frame that a lot of people have heard that says rather than just focus on climate change or just coral or just species extinction or just nuclear we have to focus on all these issues.

05:17.000 --> 05:26.000
And we have to recognize that they can inter-effect each other, that one of these issues getting worse can cascade into other ones and that sometimes the solution to one can make other ones worse.

05:26.000 --> 05:43.000
So the answer in World War Two to how do we not have nuclear war was mutually assured destruction and the Bretton Woods Global Financial System and a whole bunch of like the whole post-war order, which did mean we didn't have nuclear war between superpowers.

05:43.000 --> 05:53.000
But it was also part of what led to the six continent supply chain and exponential growth connected to a linear materials economy that have pushed us to the planetary boundaries.

05:53.000 --> 05:57.000
And so we can see solutions to some problems can end up leading to other ones.

05:57.000 --> 06:11.000
The metacrisis frame, the slight distinction from that terminology from the poly crisis is that we're not just looking at the mini crises and how they can cascade, but that there are underlying dynamics that give rise to them.

06:12.000 --> 06:16.000
Obviously humans are animals, we're part of nature.

06:16.000 --> 06:32.000
We're also pretty obviously unique when you fly into London or into New York or whatever and you look at the world you see the Anthropocene in a way that the next most environment modifying creatures are things like beavers.

06:32.000 --> 06:37.000
This is obviously a radically different scale of environment modification.

06:37.000 --> 06:48.000
And so there's something about human technology that arises from something about human mind, both our capacity to create it and then also how we utilize it.

06:48.000 --> 06:52.000
So some people look at the origin of the metacrisis starting with stone tools.

06:52.000 --> 07:00.000
Some look at it starting with the agricultural revolution and the plow or the industrial revolution or various places that I think they're all interesting.

07:00.000 --> 07:17.000
But if we simply say we have a bunch of risks to civilization's ability to continue, to continue well, that are real worth considering and different than they were historically.

07:17.000 --> 07:22.000
It's also worth stating that most early civilizations don't still exist.

07:22.000 --> 07:31.000
There is no more Egyptian or Ottoman or Byzantine or Mayan empire, and the collapse of those civilizations has been academically studied, but they weren't global civilizations.

07:31.000 --> 07:44.000
So there is some precedent that civilizations have a life cycle. We have the first six continent global civilization, meaning the tech that is recording this can't be made in any country in the world.

07:44.000 --> 07:51.000
The internet that is broadcasting this to people requires this global civilization to produce.

07:51.000 --> 07:58.000
So metacrisis. I think everyone is aware of there's a lot of risks that we face.

07:58.000 --> 08:06.000
And we can look at the economic drivers in terms of perverse incentives and externalised costs.

08:06.000 --> 08:13.000
We can look at the game theoretic rival risk drivers in terms of arms races and tragedy of the commons.

08:13.000 --> 08:19.000
We can look at the theory of technology, the way that technology itself ends up shaping mind.

08:19.000 --> 08:28.000
We can obviously look at things deep in the nature of human psychology, our value systems, our cognition.

08:28.000 --> 08:37.000
It's pretty clear when we look around that none of the other animals or plants are causing possible self-induced extinction of planetary systems.

08:37.000 --> 08:42.000
There's no planetary boundaries as a result of the activity of deer or algae or oak trees.

08:42.000 --> 08:48.000
So there's something unique about humans. Is this innate to human nature and there's no way of escaping it?

08:48.000 --> 08:53.000
Is this something that human nature can do but is not the only thing it can do?

08:53.000 --> 09:00.000
It can be conditioned, it could be conditioned differently. This is what we're here to explore today.

09:00.000 --> 09:09.000
Ian, obviously your book The Master and his Emissary kind of answers this question in a way,

09:09.000 --> 09:19.000
which is, though it's coming from a different angle, getting the master and emissary wrong would be said to be the cause of all the crises that we face, the situation we're in.

09:19.000 --> 09:28.000
For those who don't already have that framework, do you want to share your introductory thoughts on the human condition that has brought us here?

09:28.000 --> 09:43.000
Yes, I agree with you wholeheartedly that we need to look for underlying causes of a whole pattern of events that are not just unfortunate things that happen to happen.

09:43.000 --> 09:50.000
We were doing very well and then suddenly people said the climate was changing and the seas were polluted and so forth.

09:50.000 --> 10:01.000
There's a whole range of events that can be traced back to the inevitable consequence of a certain way of looking at the world.

10:01.000 --> 10:17.000
And that way of looking at the world is, in my view, associated with and driven by a model of the world that is present to the left hemisphere in a way that is not the case with the right hemisphere.

10:17.000 --> 10:26.000
In brief, the right hemisphere seems to be more in touch with presence, with what actually experience comes to us and what we inhabit.

10:26.000 --> 10:38.000
Whereas the left hemisphere is providing a representation, no longer the presence, but a map, a program, a theory, a diagram,

10:38.000 --> 10:48.000
but something abstracted, categorical, removed from and not having the characteristics of the world that it is intending to map.

10:48.000 --> 11:03.000
Now, I mean, I should say that to anybody who doesn't know my work, you've probably heard that everything to do with hemispheres is wrong and that it's outmoded and science has got past it.

11:03.000 --> 11:10.000
This is not true. If you don't know my work, then forget almost everything you think you know about hemisphere differences.

11:10.000 --> 11:13.000
They're not the ones that you were told.

11:13.000 --> 11:20.000
But there are, although we got the differences largely wrong, not entirely wrong, but mainly wrong.

11:20.000 --> 11:26.000
That doesn't mean to say that there are no differences and it wouldn't be important to find out what those differences are.

11:26.000 --> 11:28.000
That's something I've researched for about 30 years.

11:29.000 --> 11:44.000
And in short, the difference comes down to ultimately a mode of attention, which is an evolutionary development that goes back pretty much as far as we can trace it.

11:44.000 --> 11:48.000
We think back to trilobites and possibly even beyond.

11:48.000 --> 12:00.000
So this is something in which there needs to be two ways of attending to the world that are both very important but appear to be mutually incompatible.

12:00.000 --> 12:05.000
One is that with which we grasp things. We need to get things in order to survive.

12:05.000 --> 12:11.000
We need to get food. We need to handle twigs to build a nest or sticks to build a shelter, whatever it is.

12:11.000 --> 12:15.000
We need to be able to latch on to something, precisely target it and get it.

12:15.000 --> 12:26.000
And that's so important that, in a way, one whole half of one's brain is largely geared to this particular end, that of power.

12:26.000 --> 12:33.000
But if you pay only that attention to the world, then you will be very vulnerable because you won't see the predator.

12:33.000 --> 12:39.000
You won't see your conspecifics. You won't see everything else that's going on of which you need to be aware.

12:39.000 --> 12:49.000
And so, effectively, this is a difference in which one hemisphere pays a very narrowly targeted, precise attention to a detail in order to grab it.

12:49.000 --> 12:56.000
And another kind of attention which is broad, open, sustained and vigilant and on the lookout for everything else.

12:56.000 --> 12:58.000
Putting it very simply.

12:58.000 --> 13:01.000
Those two kinds of attention change what we find.

13:01.000 --> 13:08.000
No neurodigital world will dispute that the two hemispheres attend differently. It's very clear they do.

13:08.000 --> 13:13.000
And no philosopher will dispute the fact that attention changes what it is you see.

13:13.000 --> 13:20.000
So, at the end of this, fairly obviously, if we attend in two different ways, we see two different worlds.

13:20.000 --> 13:25.000
I'm going to grossly simplify here.

13:25.000 --> 13:32.000
But effectively, in one, that of the left hemisphere, the world is made up of little bits that attract attention.

13:32.000 --> 13:36.000
And they're things that we're already targeted on because we know we want them.

13:36.000 --> 13:44.000
They're isolated, they're decontextualized, they belong to categories, they're abstracted and effectively lifeless.

13:44.000 --> 13:50.000
Whereas in the right hemisphere, it sees that everything is ultimately connected.

13:50.000 --> 13:58.000
It's connected, obviously, to the context of things that are immediately around it, particularly powerful, but it's ultimately connected to everything beyond that.

13:58.000 --> 14:03.000
That the world is never fixed in the way the left hemisphere needs to fix things in order to grab them.

14:03.000 --> 14:11.000
It's not built up out of slices or pieces, but is, in fact, a whole seamless flow, a very important word.

14:11.000 --> 14:18.000
And in this right hemisphere, implicit meaning is understood because that's contextualized.

14:18.000 --> 14:24.000
And part of the context of that is emotion, the body, other people, the world at large.

14:24.000 --> 14:33.000
You've got a kind of mechanistic reductionist world, subtended by the left hemisphere, which is just a representation or a useful diagram.

14:33.000 --> 14:41.000
And you've got a living, complex world, on the other hand, which has characteristics which are very much harder to pin down,

14:41.000 --> 14:44.000
but involve all the richness and meaning in life.

14:44.000 --> 14:51.000
So what I believe, and in the masternities I'm assuming my earlier book I traced in the second part,

14:51.000 --> 14:59.000
a sort of path through the history of the West from the ancient Greeks to the modern time, in which there were rises and fallings of civilization,

14:59.000 --> 15:06.000
and in which what happened was that in each civilization, the two ways of seeing the world were used fruitfully together.

15:06.000 --> 15:09.000
And this is not a difference just between science and the arts.

15:09.000 --> 15:13.000
Science needs both kinds of attention. The arts need both kinds of attention.

15:13.000 --> 15:19.000
And this is how they flourished to begin with and were highly creative, but over a length of time they overreached themselves.

15:19.000 --> 15:22.000
They became too big. They became stereotypes.

15:22.000 --> 15:27.000
They needed global administration that could be rolled out to parts of an empire.

15:27.000 --> 15:39.000
And so we entered into a world very much like that of the left hemisphere and very soon the civilization, either the Greek or the Roman collapsed after this moment appeared.

15:39.000 --> 15:42.000
I mean, a complex story, but that's it in our play.

15:42.000 --> 15:54.000
And I think that we're in another, a third wave of this, if you like, in the West, which began in the Renaissance with an incredible flourishing

15:54.000 --> 16:06.000
and almost unequaled anywhere in the world at any time of everything, of interest in the sciences, in the heavens, in art, in sculpture, in music, in poetry.

16:06.000 --> 16:09.000
This is an incredibly rich time.

16:09.000 --> 16:20.000
And then from about the end of the 17th century, very roughly, with the scientific revolution, we began to believe that we could understand everything in terms of mechanisms.

16:20.000 --> 16:28.000
And this was a useful way to think and indeed let me be the first to say that we have benefited from it in many ways.

16:28.000 --> 16:32.000
We have developments that very few of us would wish to be without as a result of it.

16:32.000 --> 16:35.000
But unfortunately, it led to a philosophical error.

16:35.000 --> 16:39.000
And it's not just as it were a philosophical error in an abstract way.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
It's one that runs deep to the nature of how we experience the world.

16:43.000 --> 16:52.000
That is, we believe that the world is made up of parts and that we find reality by going down and down and down until we've got bits that are almost identical to one another.

16:52.000 --> 17:00.000
Whereas in fact, almost the opposite is true, that everything happens out of the coming together into complex holes.

17:00.000 --> 17:11.000
Now, when I say coming together, I'm suggesting that we do actually temporarily start from, or temporarily, from parts, but we don't.

17:11.000 --> 17:17.000
In our minds, in the left hemisphere, we start from parts, but in reality, things are whole.

17:17.000 --> 17:22.000
And what we call parts are holes of another level and they can't be understood only by the parts.

17:22.000 --> 17:31.000
This is a theory which is sometimes called a Gestalt theory, because the Germans have this word Gestalt, which we don't have an exact equivalent,

17:31.000 --> 17:36.000
or which means a hole which cannot be accounted for by the sum of the pieces, the parts.

17:36.000 --> 17:38.000
We've lost that insight.

17:38.000 --> 17:48.000
And I think that what has happened is that a combination of factors, and it's not exhaustive, but the rise of capitalism, the development of empires,

17:49.000 --> 18:02.000
both geographical empires and commercial empires, thinking in terms of global generalizations have led us away from the reality,

18:02.000 --> 18:12.000
which is always unique, implicit, wrapped up with value, not just being sort of facts on their own.

18:12.000 --> 18:21.000
Which is not to say, by the way, that I don't have any tract myself with the idea that we all just make it all up to suit ourselves.

18:21.000 --> 18:22.000
No, that's not the case.

18:22.000 --> 18:30.000
But nonetheless, our reality is something we experience as a relationship between us observing and whatever it is that it's observed.

18:30.000 --> 18:31.000
And this goes both ways.

18:31.000 --> 18:34.000
We are affected by it and we affect what we see.

18:34.000 --> 18:37.000
We literally change what there is there to see.

18:37.000 --> 18:46.000
Now, that vision is quite different from the one we have, that if only we can master more and more using left hemisphere kinds of mechanism,

18:46.000 --> 18:52.000
we will achieve power and power will make us happy, but the roots of happiness are very other than that.

18:52.000 --> 18:54.000
I'm sure we'll come on to that.

18:54.000 --> 19:03.000
But effectively, we think we've accounted for everything when we think in terms of matter, but much more important are values, a sense of purpose.

19:03.000 --> 19:06.000
And as far as I'm concerned, a sense of the sacred.

19:06.000 --> 19:13.000
That's really where we're at. And I think recovering some of what we've lost is critical to making any progress.

19:13.000 --> 19:16.000
We can't just stick sticking plasters on the cancer.

19:16.000 --> 19:25.000
We need to eradicate the cause and change the way in which we think about ourselves, the world and how we relate to it.

19:25.000 --> 19:34.000
Before we move to John's opening comments for those who aren't familiar, would you explain why you use the term master in emissary?

19:34.000 --> 19:44.000
This is a kind of a fable in which there is a wise spiritual master who looks after a small community so well that it flourishes and grows.

19:44.000 --> 19:53.000
After a while, he realizes he can't look after all the business of the community himself, not just because there's now too much of it, which is part of it,

19:53.000 --> 20:02.000
but also because if he's to maintain his overall vision and to see the whole, he mustn't get distracted by detailed bureaucratic concerns.

20:02.000 --> 20:11.000
So he appoints his brightest and best to be his emissary and go about and do the administrative stuff, a high level assistant.

20:11.000 --> 20:19.000
And unfortunately, that assistant is hubristic, knowing much less than the master he thinks he knows at all.

20:19.000 --> 20:22.000
And he thinks, in fact, of course, he is the real master.

20:22.000 --> 20:30.000
And because of his lack of knowledge of what it is he doesn't know, he, the master and the civilization fall into ruins.

20:30.000 --> 20:38.000
And that obviously is an allegory, which could be applied, I believe can be directly applied to the idea of the relationship between these hemispheres,

20:38.000 --> 20:43.000
because one of them actually sees much more is wiser.

20:43.000 --> 20:46.000
And, you know, I'm not just using figures of speech.

20:46.000 --> 20:56.000
