02:28:29.000 --> 02:28:37.000
And the Relata come out of the network of relations at the intersection points. We see things that attract our attention. There's a thing.

02:28:37.000 --> 02:28:48.000
So if that's the case, then anyway, you'd expect this divine being to want to create something that was other than itself in order to have a relationship with it.

02:28:48.000 --> 02:29:05.000
And if God is as is held in almost all spiritual traditions, love, then love needs to have another and it needs also not to compel that other, because it cannot, it cannot love something that is under entirely predictable and under its control.

02:29:06.000 --> 02:29:23.000
So that view of the cosmos, which I think is wonderfully developed in Christianity through the idea of a God that makes himself vulnerable by a creation that is free, either to reciprocate his love or not reciprocate it.

02:29:23.000 --> 02:29:32.000
I want to come back to the cabalistic story. So the first act of this creative God is not to stretch out a hand and make something happen.

02:29:33.000 --> 02:29:41.000
It's to withdraw. It's to rein itself in so that there's a space for something other. That's called Sim Tsong, which simply means withdraw.

02:29:41.000 --> 02:29:55.000
And then the second phase is called Shepharat Hekellim, which means the shattering of the vessels, because in this space that's been created, there are 12 vessels and a single spark comes out of it and it often lands on the vessels and shatters them.

02:29:55.000 --> 02:30:03.000
In fact, it only shatters eight out of the 12, explaining why it would take me too long. So let's just accept that.

02:30:03.000 --> 02:30:20.000
And then the third phase, in which humanity, according to the Judea tradition, has a particular role that only it is capable of carrying out, which is to repair the shattering, to couldn't repair.

02:30:20.000 --> 02:30:32.000
And the idea is that we are tasked with creating again these vessels so that they are more beautiful than they were before they were shattered.

02:30:32.000 --> 02:30:49.000
And the image that always comes to mind for me here is the Japanese art of Kintsugi, whereby a piece of ceramics that is broken is repaired, sometimes with lines of gold, and is considered more special, more precious, more beautiful afterwards than it was before.

02:30:49.000 --> 02:31:10.000
Now, if it is true that we have the capacity to see how to repair things, and no other beings can see that, and I think that is probably right, there's no disrespect to the rest of animal life, that probably we have this ability to see other things and see beyond and foresee things in a way that they probably don't.

02:31:10.000 --> 02:31:26.000
So I think if that's the case, then we have a special role there, and we may even have a role in bringing about the existence of God, because that may sound very strange, and possibly blasphemous, but the way in which I think this works is like this.

02:31:26.000 --> 02:31:41.000
We all know Pascal's wager, Pascal's wager with a simple one, either there is a God or there isn't. If there is a God, then it's very important that we should recognize and reciprocate our relationship with that God.

02:31:41.000 --> 02:31:46.000
If there is no God, then it won't do us any harm to behave as if there was a God.

02:31:47.000 --> 02:32:05.000
But I think there's a third possibility, which is McGilchrist's wager, and it has the first two of Pascal in it, but there was a third one, which is that maybe we play a role in the development, the evolution, the furtherment, the fulfillment of whatever is divine.

02:32:05.000 --> 02:32:19.000
So if that's the case, then once again we have an incredibly ennobling obligation, which is to make sure that we do help that good progress in the world.

02:32:19.000 --> 02:32:30.000
So on various levels to do with how we dispose our attention, the role we play in repair, the role we play in furthering and bringing about the divine, we can influence things.

02:32:30.000 --> 02:32:46.000
